<li class="commentbody" id="comment-561739">
			<cite><a href='https://mail.google.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>jenna</a></cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-561739" title="">January 22, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">235</div>

				<p>I made these the other day, and they are fantastic.  Seemed to taste like cookie dough, so I went with using a very small biscuit cutter ( I can&#8217;t seem to cut a straight line) and made them like little  cookie bites.  I also upped the cinnamon, so it had more sass to it.  Result was a cookie-graham, I suppose. Great base recipe, versatile.  Thanks for posting it.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-565827">
			<cite><a href='http://www.justaroughdraft.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Anna</a></cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-565827" title="">January 30, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">236</div>

				<p>Mmmm! I just made these and they are deeelicious! I made them with graham flour + APF and they came out perfect. Thanks so much for the recipe. This one is definitely a keeper. :)</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-586971">
			<cite>Julia</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-586971" title="">February 12, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">237</div>

				<p>I just made these, gluten free. Thought I&#8217;d give my substitutions in case anyone else wants to try. In place of the flours, I used:</p>
<p>2-1/4 cup brown rice flour<br />
3/4 cup potato starch<br />
2 T gf flour substitute<br />
1/2 t. xanthan gum</p>
<p>The rest I made the same. It came out nicely (although the texture was slightly rice flour-y), but I might back off the vanilla a touch.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-589936">
			<cite>Jessica</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-589936" title="">February 19, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">238</div>

				<p>If anyone else finds themselves in a hurry, I&#8217;ve found they disappear just as quickly when you simply roll the dough out on parchment paper and bake as one giant cookie&#8230;  I use a pizza cutter to slice it up into squares just after it comes out of the oven.  The edges are a bit, er, rustic&#8230; but I haven&#8217;t heard any complaints! Very good and easy kid treat.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-595053">
			<cite>Miss Martina</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-595053" title="">March 3, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">239</div>

				<p>Thank you, I like &#8216;em &#8211; a whole bunch!! I believe they should be called &#8216;Graham Wafers&#8217;. Used a half-cup of whole wheat + half-cup oat flour + 2 Tbsp of rice flour (+ balance unbleached AP) &#8211; all sifted together. I think that helped keep the crispness. MM-</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
